{
  "In linear regression, the least-squares solution minimizes ||Ax - b||^2. The normal equation for this is:": "",
  "Ax = b": "",
  "x = A b": "",
  "A^(-1) x = b": "",
  "A^T A x = A^T b": "",
  "The normal equation A^T A x = A^T b is derived by setting the gradient of ||Ax - b||^2 to zero. The solution x = (A^T A)^(-1) A^T b gives the best linear fit in the least-squares sense.": "",
  "In a neural network, weights are typically stored as matrices. If a layer maps 100 inputs to 50 outputs, what are the dimensions of its weight matrix?": "",
  "50 x 100": "",
  "100 x 50": "",
  "50 x 50": "",
  "100 x 100": "",
  "The weight matrix W maps input x (100-dim) to output y = Wx (50-dim). For this matrix-vector product to work, W must be 50 x 100.": "",
  "Orthogonality plays a key role in gradient descent. At a local minimum, the gradient is orthogonal to:": "",
  "The level set (contour) of the loss function": "",
  "The weight vector": "",
  "The data matrix": "",
  "Nothing in particular; the gradient is the zero vector at a minimum": "",
  "At a local minimum, the gradient equals the zero vector (all partial derivatives are zero). The gradient is perpendicular to level sets at non-critical points, not at the minimum itself.": "",
  "In Support Vector Machines (SVMs), the optimal separating hyperplane is defined by w . x + b = 0. The orthogonal distance from a point x0 to this hyperplane is:": "",
  "w . x0 + b": "",
  "|w . x0|": "",
  "||w|| * ||x0||": "",
  "|w . x0 + b| / ||w||": "",
  "The orthogonal (perpendicular) distance from point x0 to the hyperplane w . x + b = 0 is |w . x0 + b| / ||w||. SVMs maximize this margin for the closest points (support vectors).": "",
  "The kernel trick in SVMs implicitly computes inner products in a higher-dimensional space. What is the polynomial kernel of degree 2 for vectors x and y in R^2?": "",
  "K(x, y) = (x . y + 1)^2": "",
  "K(x, y) = ||x - y||^2": "",
  "K(x, y) = exp(-||x - y||^2)": "",
  "K(x, y) = x . y": "",
  "The polynomial kernel of degree 2 is K(x,y) = (x . y + c)^2 (commonly c = 1). This computes the inner product in a feature space that includes all monomials up to degree 2 without explicitly constructing the high-dimensional features.": "",
  "In collaborative filtering, a ratings matrix R (users x items) is approximately factored as R ~ UV^T. If there are 1000 users, 500 items, and 10 latent factors, what are the dimensions of U and V?": "",
  "U is 1000x500, V is 500x10": "",
  "U is 10x1000, V is 10x500": "",
  "U is 1000x10, V is 500x10": "",
  "U is 1000x500, V is 500x1000": "",
  "With 10 latent factors, U (1000x10) holds user embeddings and V (500x10) holds item embeddings. The approximation R ~ UV^T produces a 1000x500 matrix as required.": "",
  "Batch normalization in neural networks involves computing the mean and variance of activations. The whitening transformation (decorrelation) is related to which linear algebra concept?": "",
  "Determinant calculation": "",
  "Gaussian elimination": "",
  "Cross product computation": "",
  "Eigenvalue decomposition of the covariance matrix": "",
  "Whitening decorrelates features by projecting data onto the eigenvectors of the covariance matrix and scaling by inverse square roots of eigenvalues. This is equivalent to transforming the covariance to the identity matrix.": "",
  "In word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec), words are represented as vectors. If 'king' - 'man' + 'woman' ~ 'queen', this relies on what property of the vector space?": "",
  "Orthogonality of all word vectors": "",
  "Linear algebraic structure where semantic relationships are encoded as vector arithmetic": "",
  "The embedding matrix being orthogonal": "",
  "All word vectors having unit norm": "",
  "Word embeddings capture semantic relationships as directions in vector space. The relationship 'king - man + woman ~ queen' shows that gender is encoded as a consistent vector direction, demonstrating the linear algebraic structure of the embedding space.": "",
  "The condition number of the matrix A^T A affects the convergence of gradient descent for linear regression. A high condition number means:": "",
  "The solution does not exist": "",
  "Slow convergence due to elongated contours of the loss function": "",
  "Fast convergence": "",
  "The problem is well-conditioned and easy to solve": "",
  "A high condition number means the eigenvalues of A^T A vary widely, creating elongated elliptical contours. Gradient descent oscillates in narrow valleys, converging slowly. Preconditioning or using adaptive methods can help.": "",
  "In a convolutional neural network, a convolution operation can be expressed as multiplication by a Toeplitz matrix. This matrix has what special structure?": "",
  "All entries are either 0 or 1": "",
  "Each descending diagonal has constant values": "",
  "It is always orthogonal": "",
  "Diagonal entries are all different": "",
  "A Toeplitz matrix has constant values along each descending diagonal, reflecting the translation-invariant nature of convolution. The kernel weights appear shifted along the diagonals.": "",
  "What is a 'feature vector' in machine learning?": "",
  "A vector that points toward the nearest class boundary": "",
  "The gradient of the loss function": "",
  "The weight vector of a trained model": "",
  "A numerical representation of a data point as a vector of attribute values": "",
  "A feature vector is a point in a high-dimensional space where each coordinate represents a measurable attribute of the data. Machine learning algorithms operate on these vector representations.": "",
  "What does 'cosine similarity' measure between two vectors?": "",
  "The product of their norms": "",
  "The sum of their components": "",
  "The Euclidean distance between them": "",
  "The cosine of the angle between the vectors, computed as (u . v) / (||u|| ||v||)": "",
  "Cosine similarity measures the angle between two vectors, ranging from -1 (opposite) to +1 (same direction). It is widely used in information retrieval and recommendation systems because it ignores magnitude and focuses on direction.": "",
  "What is 'regularization' in the context of linear models?": "",
  "Using a regular (non-singular) matrix for the weights": "",
  "Normalizing the input data to have zero mean": "",
  "Ensuring the weight matrix is orthogonal": "",
  "Adding a penalty term (like ||w||^2) to the loss function to prevent overfitting": "",
  "Regularization adds a penalty like lambda * ||w||^2 (L2/Ridge) or lambda * ||w||_1 (L1/Lasso) to the loss function. This discourages large weights, reducing overfitting and improving generalization.": "",
  "What is the 'Hessian matrix' in optimization for machine learning?": "",
  "The weight matrix of the neural network": "",
  "The data matrix of training examples": "",
  "The identity matrix used for regularization": "",
  "The matrix of second partial derivatives of the loss function with respect to the parameters": "",
  "The Hessian H has entries H_ij = d^2L/dw_i dw_j. Its eigenvalues indicate curvature: positive eigenvalues mean the function curves upward (local minimum direction), negative means downward (local maximum direction), and mixed indicates a saddle point.": "",
  "What is a 'latent factor' in matrix factorization for recommendation systems?": "",
  "A hidden feature dimension that captures underlying patterns in user-item interactions": "",
  "The delay between a user's rating and the system's response": "",
  "An item that no user has rated": "",
  "A missing value in the ratings matrix": "",
  "Latent factors are hidden dimensions discovered by matrix factorization. For movies, latent factors might correspond to genres, era, mood, or other abstract qualities that explain rating patterns.": "",
  "What does 'embedding' mean in machine learning?": "",
  "A learned mapping from discrete or high-dimensional objects to continuous low-dimensional vectors": "",
  "Removing features from the dataset": "",
  "Placing data points into a database": "",
  "Training a model on embedded systems": "",
  "An embedding maps objects (words, users, items) to dense vectors in a low-dimensional space. These vector representations capture semantic similarity -- similar objects have nearby embeddings.": "",
  "What is 'spectral clustering' in machine learning?": "",
  "A clustering method that uses eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a similarity or Laplacian matrix": "",
  "Clustering data based on light spectrum wavelengths": "",
  "K-means clustering applied in Fourier space": "",
  "A method that only works on 2D data": "",
  "Spectral clustering constructs a graph Laplacian from the data similarity matrix, then uses its smallest eigenvectors to embed data in a low-dimensional space where clusters are easily separable.": "",
  "What does 'orthogonal regularization' mean in neural network training?": "",
  "Training with perpendicular gradient updates": "",
  "Regularizing the orthogonal complement of the weight space": "",
  "Using only orthogonal matrices as network weights": "",
  "Adding a penalty that encourages weight matrices to be close to orthogonal": "",
  "Orthogonal regularization adds a penalty like ||W^T W - I||^2 to encourage weight matrices to be approximately orthogonal. This helps preserve gradient norms during backpropagation, mitigating vanishing/exploding gradients.": "",
  "What is the 'Moore-Penrose pseudoinverse' used for in machine learning?": "",
  "Computing eigenvalues efficiently under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "Computing the minimum-norm least-squares solution for potentially non-square or singular systems": "",
  "Inverting any square matrix, particularly regarding pseudoinverse as": "",
  "Transposing a rectangular matrix following the established framework": "",
  "The Moore-Penrose pseudoinverse A^+ generalizes matrix inversion to non-square and singular matrices. It gives the minimum-norm least-squares solution x = A^+ b and can be computed via SVD.": "",
  "What does 'attention mechanism' in transformers compute using inner products?": "",
  "Similarity scores between query and key vectors to determine how much each value contributes to the output": "",
  "The inverse of the input embedding": "",
  "The eigenvalues of the attention matrix": "",
  "The determinant of the input matrix": "",
  "Attention computes scores as dot products of query and key vectors: score(Q, K) = QK^T / sqrt(d_k). These scores, after softmax, weight the value vectors to produce context-aware representations.": "",
  "A data scientist fits a linear regression model y = w1*x1 + w2*x2 + b to 100 data points. The design matrix A is 100x3 (including a column of 1s for the bias). What is the dimension of A^T A?": "",
  "3 x 100": "",
  "3 x 3": "",
  "100 x 3": "",
  "A is 100x3, so A^T is 3x100, and A^T A is 3x3. This small system is computationally easy to solve, giving the least-squares weights.": "",
  "A recommendation engine uses matrix factorization to predict missing ratings. If user i's embedding is u_i = (2, 1) and item j's embedding is v_j = (3, 4), what is the predicted rating?": "",
  "7": "",
  "5": "",
  "11": "",
  "10": "",
  "The predicted rating is u_i . v_j = 2*3 + 1*4 = 6 + 4 = 10. The dot product of user and item embeddings estimates how much the user would like the item.": "",
  "A natural language processing engineer computes cosine similarity between document vectors d1 = (3, 4) and d2 = (4, 3). What is the cosine similarity?": "",
  "7/25": "",
  "24/25": "",
  "1": "",
  "12/25": "",
  "cos(theta) = (d1 . d2) / (||d1|| ||d2||) = (12 + 12) / (5 * 5) = 24/25 = 0.96. The documents are very similar in direction.": "",
  "A machine learning engineer uses Ridge regression (L2 regularization) with parameter lambda. The solution is x = (A^T A + lambda*I)^(-1) A^T b. What does adding lambda*I to A^T A accomplish numerically?": "",
  "It doubles the size of the matrix": "",
  "It removes the smallest eigenvalue": "",
  "It makes all eigenvalues zero": "",
  "It shifts all eigenvalues up by lambda, ensuring the matrix is invertible and well-conditioned": "",
  "Adding lambda*I shifts every eigenvalue from sigma_i to sigma_i + lambda. This ensures all eigenvalues are at least lambda > 0, making the matrix positive definite and invertible, even when A^T A is singular.": "",
  "A deep learning researcher initializes a recurrent neural network with an orthogonal weight matrix. Why is this initialization strategy beneficial?": "",
  "It eliminates the need for a bias term": "",
  "It ensures the network outputs are always positive": "",
  "It preserves gradient norms during backpropagation, mitigating vanishing and exploding gradients": "",
  "It makes training faster by reducing the number of parameters": "",
  "Orthogonal matrices have all singular values equal to 1, so multiplying by them preserves vector norms. In RNNs, this prevents gradients from shrinking (vanishing) or growing (exploding) through many time steps.": "",
  "A computer vision engineer uses the Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) to compress a 1000x1000 image by keeping only the top 50 singular values. How many values need to be stored?": "",
  "2,500": "",
  "1,000,000": "",
  "50,000": "",
  "100,050": "",
  "A rank-50 SVD stores: 50 left singular vectors (1000 entries each) + 50 right singular vectors (1000 entries each) + 50 singular values = 50*1000 + 50*1000 + 50 = 100,050. This is about 10% of the original 1,000,000 entries.": "",
  "A text analytics team builds a topic model using Non-negative Matrix Factorization (NMF) on a 5000-document x 10000-word matrix V ~ WH. If they want 20 topics, what are the dimensions of W and H?": "",
  "W is 20x5000, H is 10000x20": "",
  "W is 20x20, H is 20x20": "",
  "W is 5000x10000, H is 10000x20": "",
  "W is 5000x20, H is 20x10000": "",
  "With 20 topics, W (5000x20) gives each document's topic weights, and H (20x10000) gives each topic's word distribution. The product WH approximates the original 5000x10000 matrix.": "",
  "A fraud detection system uses Mahalanobis distance, which is defined as d(x) = sqrt((x-mu)^T S^(-1) (x-mu)) where S is the covariance matrix. Why is this preferable to Euclidean distance for anomaly detection?": "",
  "It accounts for correlations between features and different variances along different directions": "",
  "It can only be computed for 2D data": "",
  "It does not require knowledge of the data distribution": "",
  "It is always smaller than Euclidean distance": "",
  "Mahalanobis distance uses the inverse covariance matrix to normalize by the data's spread in each direction and account for correlations. A point far from the mean in a low-variance direction is more anomalous than one equally far in a high-variance direction.": "",
  "A speech recognition system uses an orthogonal transformation to convert mel-spectrogram features. If the transformation matrix Q is 40x40 orthogonal, what is the computational benefit of using Q^T instead of Q^(-1)?": "",
  "Q^T has fewer non-zero entries": "",
  "There is no computational benefit": "",
  "Transposing is O(n^2) while inverting is O(n^3), so Q^T is much faster to compute": "",
  "Q^T is more numerically accurate than Q^(-1)": "",
  "For orthogonal Q, Q^(-1) = Q^T. Computing a transpose is O(n^2) (just rearranging entries) while computing a general inverse is O(n^3). For a 40x40 matrix, this means 1,600 vs ~64,000 operations.": "",
  "A reinforcement learning agent uses a neural network with weight matrices W1 (100x50) and W2 (50x10). The total number of trainable weight parameters (excluding biases) is:": "",
  "5,500": "",
  "160": "",
  "5,000": "",
